I prepared a unit test to make the issue's investigation easier. Because the kill does not work if you start the test multiple times you have to kill the previously started commands yourself, otherwise the test will fail.

``` java
@Test(timeout = 10000)
public void test_signal_kill() throws Exception {       
    SSHClient sshClient = new SSHClient();
    sshClient.addHostKeyVerifier(new PromiscuousVerifier());
    sshClient.connect("192.168.1.1", 22);
    sshClient.authPassword("USERNAME", "PASSWORD");

    Session session = sshClient.startSession();
    Command cmd = session.exec("sleep 2498");
    cmd.signal(Signal.KILL);
    Thread.sleep(2000);

    session = sshClient.startSession();
    Command ps = session.exec("ps -eo pid,args | grep 'sleep 2498'");
    String output = IOUtils.readFully(ps.getInputStream()).toString();
    assertTrue(StringUtils.isBlank(output));
}
